[FEN "6k1/8/p6p/1p1pP2P/8/1P5K/P7/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2023.02.11"]
[UTCTime "22:12:04"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ White to play and win. }
1. Kg4 Kf7 2. Kf5 b4 3. e6+ Ke7 4. Ke5 d4 5. Kxd4 Kxe6 6. Kc5 (6. Kc4 { This also works but Kc5 is more direct because it threatens the b pawn, has access to the b6 square, and shoulders the king from d6. }) 6... Kf5 7. Kxb4 { The only move! If white tries to take the a pawn first, then black promotes first and wins. } 7... Kg5 8. a4 (8. Ka5 { This natural move throws away the win and allows black to enter a drawn queen ending. }) (8. Kc5 { This also works but play a4 for the continuation. }) (8. Kc3 { This also works but play a4 for the continuation. }) (8. Kc4 { Amazingly this throws away the win because black will enter a drawn queen endgame. }) 8... Kxh5 9. Kc3 (9. Ka3 { This also works but play Kc3 for the continuation. }) (9. Kc5 { This also works but play Kc3 for the continuation. }) 9... Kg4 10. b4 h5 11. b5 axb5 12. a5 { The only move! White must queen on a8 to cover black's promotion square on h1. } *


